Discussion for Problem 1¶

We can see that the better model for the given dataset is the one without the alpha intercept. It has much higher R-squared and the beta parameter is statistically significant. We see that the beta value is slightly above one. This means that the model assumes always some small incease over the previous values. Obviously, it fails to forecasts well if this is not the case as it the last few periods. However, the high R-squared really shows that the previous values is really important when forecasting the series. It seems we do have serial correlation at play here.

Data Descriptions¶

I used ETF from Yahoo finance that mirrors gold. I used the daily Adjusted Close series. I choose to work with the dates 2013-05-01 to 2017-09-01 as it simplifies the problem. I looked at the whole history initially however the history is too log and there is too much going on over last 20 years.

ADF Test¶

We will test it for stationarity used ADF test.

In [23]:
# test the original series
results = adf(df_AC.values.ravel())
print_ADF_results(results, 0.05)

Test Statistic: -2.88804
p value: 0.04676
Number of lags used: 10
Number of observations used for the ADF regression and calculation of the critical values: 1084
Critical values for the test statistic at the 1 %, 5 %, and 10 % levels. Based on MacKinnon (2010): {'1%': -3.4363969122132692, '5%': -2.8642099630802869, '10%': -2.5681915787162484}
The maximized information criterion if autolag is not None: 3356.39082

The above series is likely stationary at 0.05 confidence.

Basically, what this means that that the gold prices are I(0) stationary. This took me a while to figure. It is expected that the differences of series are I(0) but this is not the case. In addition, this series is stationary in the sample I picked. If we would change the time period, we could get different series that is not stationary.

Let's test the difference series anyway.

The difference series is stationary as well however the problem is the below. We have no serial correlations in the differences. So, we can't use ARMA model over the differences of the series. We have to use ARMA model for the actual series.

ARIMA model¶

We can see that we have AR and possibly one MA autocorrelation in the series. One option to model the dynamics of the price is ARMA(2,1). It is one of the best fits that I found. Other lags are also possible to take into account however the statsmodels packages is not very flexible in estimating the best fit. I run a number of ARMA models and the below is one of the best ones.

Covariance estimator: robust

This GARCH model is superior to the ARMA model as it has lower AIC and it handles Student's t distribution in the estimation. This way we are capturing fat tails in the process.

Let's see if the residuals from this model are normal.

NormaltestResult(statistic=84.636149153875706, pvalue=4.1830564603773235e-19)

We can see that the residuals from the GARCH model are not normally distributed. This means that we are picking up all statistical properties of the series well. Particularly, we have fat tails in the residual.

def plot_hist(array=np.array(0), set_name='set_name'):
    """
    Plots the histogram for data - an array object.
    Normal distribution fit is add
    
    :REMEMBER: Assumes that if the data point is zero then there was no trading and so it is filtered out.
    """
    array = array[array!=0]

    with mpl.rc_context():
        mpl.rc("figure", figsize=(20,10))
        
        plt.figure()
        x = np.linspace(array.mean() - 3 * array.std(),
                            array.mean() + 3 * array.std())
        
        plt.plot(x,
                 scs.norm.pdf(x, array.mean(), array.std()),
                 'r',
                 lw=2.0,
                 label='fitted_normal-3_deviations')
        
        sns.distplot(array,
                      color='b',
                      kde_kws={"label": "Return kde - " + set_name},
                      hist_kws={"label": "Return hist - " + set_name})
        
        plt.draw()
        
    return None

def describe_series(pd_series, set_name):
    """
    Returns descriptive statistics for pandas series object

    :param pd_series: pd.Series object - carries all data
    :param set_name: str - you can use this to set up custom name for plots
    :return: None
    """
    assert isinstance(pd_series, pd.Series), "Pass in a 'pd.Series' object to 'pd_series' variable when calling 'describe_series' function"
    assert isinstance(set_name, str), "Pass in a string variable to 'set_name' parameter when calling 'describe_series' function"

    np_series_values = pd_series.values

    line_size = .1
    if len(np_series_values) < 10:
        line_size = .25
    elif len(np_series_values) < 50:
        line_size = .20
    elif len(np_series_values) <= 100:
        line_size = .00125
    elif len(np_series_values) > 900:
        line_size = .0125
    elif len(np_series_values) > 400:
        line_size = .02
    elif len(np_series_values) > 150:
        line_size = .05
    elif len(np_series_values) > 120:
        line_size = .06
    elif len(np_series_values) > 100:
        line_size = .08

#    line_size = 0.0005

    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=2, figsize=(15, 10))

    pd_series.plot(ax=axes[0, 0], title='Close price-' + str(set_name),  marker='.', color='r')
    axes[0, 0].tick_params(labelsize=6)
    axes[0, 0].grid(b=True, which='major', color='0.75', linestyle='dotted')

    pd_series.plot(ax=axes[0, 1], kind='hist', title='Histogram-price frequecies- ' + str(set_name))
    pd_series.plot.box(ax=axes[1, 1], vert=False, title='Box Plot - ' + str(set_name))
    pd_series.plot(ax=axes[1, 0], kind='density', title='Empirical propability density - ' + str(set_name),
                   linestyle='-')
    axes[1, 0].vlines(np_series_values.mean(), line_size, 0, color='r', linestyle='dashed', label='Mean')
    axes[1, 0].vlines(np.median(np_series_values), line_size, 0, color='y', linestyle='dashed', label='Median')
    axes[1, 0].vlines(np.median(np_series_values) + np.std(np_series_values), line_size, 0, color='g',
                      linestyle='dashed', label='+Std')
    axes[1, 0].vlines(np.median(np_series_values) - np.std(np_series_values), line_size, 0, color='g',
                      linestyle='dashed', label='-Std')
    axes[1, 0].vlines(np.median(np_series_values) + 2 * np.std(np_series_values), line_size, 0, color='m',
                      linestyle='dotted', label='+2Std')
    axes[1, 0].vlines(np.median(np_series_values) - 2 * np.std(np_series_values), line_size, 0, color='m',
                      linestyle='dotted', label='-2Std')
    axes[1, 0].vlines(np.min(np_series_values), line_size, 0, color='k', linestyle='dashed', label='Min')
    axes[1, 0].vlines(np.max(np_series_values), line_size, 0, color='k', linestyle='dashed', label='Min')
    axes[1, 0].grid(b=True, which='major', color='0.75', linestyle='dotted')
    axes[1, 0].legend(['Close', 'Mean', 'Median', '+1 Std', '-1 Std', '+2 std', '-2 Std', 'Min', 'Max'],
                      loc='best')

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

    del line_size, np_series_values
    print("\nDescriptive statistics for " + set_name + " are:")
    print(pd_series.describe())
    return None

def print_ADF_results(results, critical_value):
    """
    prints out the results with some comments for ADF test
    """
    # http://www.statsmodels.org/stable/generated/statsmodels.tsa.stattools.adfuller.html
    print("\nTest Statistic: " + "%.5f" % results[0])
    print("p value: " + "%.5f" % results[1])
    print("Number of lags used: " + "%.0f" % results[2])
    print("Number of observations used for the ADF regression and calculation of the critical values: " + "%.0f" % results[3])
    print("Critical values for the test statistic at the 1 %, 5 %, and 10 % levels. Based on MacKinnon (2010): " + str(results[4])) 
    print("The maximized information criterion if autolag is not None: "  + "%.5f" % results[5])
    
    if results[1] < critical_value:
        print("\nThe above series is likely stationary at " + str(critical_value) + " confidence.")
    else:
        print("\nThe above series is unlikely stationary at " + str(critical_value) + " confidence.")
